CloudTrail, who did what.

CloudTrail records every A-P-I call made in your A-W-S account, console clicks, C-L-I invocations, S-D-K calls, and service-to-service calls. Every event captures the same five fields. Who, the I-A-M principal, whether a user, a role, a federated identity, or an A-W-S service. What, the A-P-I action, like RunInstances, PutObject, CreateBucket, or DeleteTrail. When, the timestamp. Where, the source I-P address, user agent, and region. And the result, success or an error code, plus the request and response parameters. It's the audit trail behind every who-did-that question, and the foundation of incident investigation.

There are three event types. Management events are control-plane operations, creating, modifying, and deleting resources, I-A-M, and network changes; they're on by default and the first copy is free. Data events are data-plane operations, S3 GetObject, Lambda Invoke, DynamoDB reads; they're opt-in and charged, because the volume is huge. And Insights events are machine-learning-flagged anomalies in A-P-I volume, like a sudden spike in TerminateInstances; also opt-in and charged.

To get CloudTrail right, three things. A multi-region trail delivered to an S3 bucket captures every region in one place, and that's the standard baseline. Log file validation plus S3 Object Lock detect and prevent tampering, which is critical for compliance because an attacker's first move is often to call DeleteTrail. And delivering the trail to CloudWatch Logs lets you alarm on sensitive actions in near-real-time, like a root login or a DeleteTrail call.
